<h1>To the Massachusetts Council</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Gentn</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge 26th Feb: 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>As I am making all possible preparation to take possession of the heights of Dorchester (which I expect I shall be able to accomplish by the last of this Week)<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> it is expected that this, if any thing can, will bring the Enemy out of Boston to oppose, as at Charles-town,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> our erecting any Works there. To weaken our Lines on the North side of Cambridge River too much, with a view to strengthen those of Dorchester, before any move is made that way by the Enemy, might expose an opening they would gladly avail themselves of<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0003-ptr">3</a>and to delay it till<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> an attack is begun would be too late, as the contest will soon be decided for or against Us, after this happens.</p>
<p>Under this State of the Matter, and to avoid risking a Defeat when Victory, under Providence, may be reduced to a certainty,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> I submit it to the Wisdom of your Board if it will not<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> be best to direct the Militia of some of the Towns<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0007" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> most contiguous to Dorchester and Roxbury to repair to the Lines at those two
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0369">[369]</span>
places with there Arms, Ammunition, and Accoutrements Instantly upon a Signal given.</p>
<p>If you approve of this you will please to fix with General Thomas (who waits upon you on purpose)<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0008" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0008-ptr">8</a> upon the Signals to be given, and Issue your notice thereof accordingly.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0009" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0009-ptr">9</a> I have the honour to be with great respect &amp; esteem Gentn Yr Most Obedt Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr> (photocopy), <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Record Group (designating the location of documents in the National Archives) ]">RG</span> 93, Photocopies of State Records; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, in GWs writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read by the latter end of this Week.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>GW is referring to the Battle of Bunker Hill on 17 June 1775.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read before any movement is made that way by the Enemy, may neither be consistent with prudence, or good policy.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read till after.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read to avoid putting an affair of so much Importance to a doubtful Issue when, under Providence, it may be reduced to a certainty.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read whether it might not.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy reads of certn Towns, and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> reads of certain Towns.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read for that purpose.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0273-fn-0009">9</a>
    
   <p>Ezekiel Price, who was residing at Stoughton several miles south of Roxbury, wrote in his diary entry for 1 Mar.: Hear that orders are sent for seven regiments of the militia this way, to be ready to march upon the signal for an alarm; each man to be well provided with arms, and to carry three days provisions, dressed: the militia the other way to be in like readiness. On one side, the militia are to man the lines while our army takes possession of Dorchester Hill: on the other side, they propose to go to Noddles Island (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Diary of Ezekiel Price, 17756. &lt;i&gt;Proceedings of the Massachusetts Historical Society&lt;/i&gt; 7 (186364): 185262. ]">Prices Diary,</span> 239). For the calling out of these militiamen, see also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0309" class="document">GW to Hancock, 79 Mar. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
